t’s getting!” She was close behind it when she turned the corner, but the Rabbit was no longer to be seen: she found herself in a long, low hall, which was lit up by a row of lamps hanging from the roof.</p>\r\n\r\n		<p>There were doors all round the hall, but they were all locked; and when Alice had been all the way down one side and up the other, trying every door, she walked sadly down the middle, wondering how she was ever to get out again.</p>\r\n\r\n		<p>Suddenly she came upon a little three-legged table, all made of solid glass: there was nothing on it but a tiny golden key, and Alice’s first idea was that this might belong to one of the doors of the hall; but alas! either the locks were too large, or the key was too small, but at any rate it would not open any of them. However, on the second time round, she came upon a low curtain she had not noticed before, and behind it was a little door about fifteen inches high: she tried the little golden key in the lock, and to her great delight it fitted!</p>\r\n\r\n		<p>Alice opened the door and found that it led into a small passage, not much larger than a rat-hole: she knelt down and looked along the passage into the loveliest garden you ever saw. How she longed to get out of that dark hall, and wander about among those beds of bright flowers and those cool fountains, but she could not even get her head through the doorway; “and even if my head <em>would</em> go through,” thought poor Alice, “it would be of very little use without my shoulders. Oh, how I wish I could shut up like a telescope! I think I could, if I only knew how to begin.” For, you see, so many out-of-the-way things had happened lately, that Alice had begun to think that very few things indeed were really impossible.		</p>\r\n\r\n		<p>There seemed to be no use in waiting by the little door, so she went back to the table, half hoping she might find another key on it, or at any rate a book of rules for shutting people up like telescopes: this time she found a little bottle on it (\"which certainly was not here before,” said Alice), and tied round the neck of the bottle was a paper label, with the words “DRINK ME” beautifully printed on it in large letters.</p>\r\n\r\n		<p>It was all very well to say “Drink me,” but the wise little Alice was not going to do <em>that</em> in a hurry. “No, I’ll look first,” she said, “and see whether it’s marked ’<em>poison</em>’ or not\"; for she had read several nice little stories about children who had got burned, and eaten up by wild beasts, and other unpleasant things, all because they <em>would</em> not remember the simple rules their friends had taught them: such as, that a red-hot poker will burn you if you hold it too long; and that, if you cut your finger <em>very</em> deeply with a knife, it usually bleeds; and she had never forgotten that, if you drink much from a bottle marked “poison,” it is almost certain to disagree with you, sooner or later.</p>\r\n\r\n		<p>However, this bottle was <em>not</em> marked “poison,” so Alice ventured to taste it, and, finding it very nice (it had, in fact, a sort of mixed flavor of cherry-tart, custard, pine-apple, roast turkey, toffy, and hot buttered toast), she very soon finished it off.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n		<p>“What a curious feeling!” said Alice. “I must be shutting up like a telescope!”</p>\r\n\r\n		<p>And so it was indeed: she was now only ten inches high, and her face brightened up at the thought that she was now the right size for going through the little door into that lovely garden. First, however, she waited for a few minutes to see if she was going to shrink any further: she felt a little nervous about this; “for it might end, you know,” said Alice to herself, “in my going out altogether, like a candle. I wonder what I should be like then?” And she tried to fancy what the flame of a candle looks like after the candle is blown out, for she could not remember ever having seen such a thing.</p>\r\n\r\n		<p>After a while, finding that nothing more happened, she decided on going into the garden at once; but, alas for poor Alice! when she got to the door, she found she had forgotten the little golden key, and when she went back to the table for it, she found she could not possibly reach it: she could see it quite plainly through the glass, and she tried her best to climb up one of the legs of the table, but it was too slippery; and when she had tired herself out with trying, the poor little thing sat down and cried.</p>\r\n\r\n		<p>“Come, there’s no use in crying like that!” said Alice to herself rather sharply. “I advise you to leave off this minute!” She generally gave herself very good advice (though she very seldom followed it), and sometimes she scolded herself so severely as to bring tears into her eyes; and once she remembered trying to box her own ears for having cheated herself in a game of croquet she was playing against herself, for this curious child was very fond of pretending to be two people. “But it’s no use now,” thought poor Alice, “to pretend to be two people! Why, there’s hardly enough of me left to make\r\n			<em>one</em> respectable person!”</p>\r\n\r\n		<p>Soon her eye fell on a little glass box that was lying under the table: she opened it, and found in it a very small cake, on which the words “EAT ME” were beautifully marked in currants. “Well, I’ll eat it,” said Alice, “and if it makes me grow larger, I can reach the key; and if it makes me grow smaller, I can creep under the door: so either way I’ll get into the garden, and I don’t care which happens!”</p>\r\n\r\n		<p>She ate a little bit, and said anxiously to herself, “Which way? Which way?” holding her hand on the top of her head to feel which way it was growing; and she was quite surprised to find that she remained the same size. To be sure, this is what generally happens when one eats cake; but Alice had got so much into the way of expecting nothing but out-of-the-way things to happen, that it seemed quite dull and stupid for life to go on in the common way.</p>\r\n\r\n		<p>So she set to work, and very soon finished off the cake.</p>','Murray','','inherit','closed','closed','','47791-revision-v1','','','2017-03-05 01:31:38','2017-03-05 01:31:38','',47791,'https://redrambles.blog//47791-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(47818,1,'2017-03-05 01:33:30','2017-03-05 01:33:30','a:7:{s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"tab\";s:12:\"instructions\";s:0:\"\";s:8:\"required\";i:0;s:17:\"conditional_logic\";i:0;s:7:\"wrapper\";a:3:{s:5:\"width\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"class\";s:0:\"\";s:2:\"id\";s:0:\"\";}s:9:\"placement\";s:3:\"top\";s:8:\"endpoint\";i:0;}','Images','images','publish','closed','closed','','field_58bb6a839f5c1','','','2017-03-05 01:33:30','2017-03-05 01:33:30','',47794,'https://redrambles.blog//?post_type=acf-field&p=47818',1,'acf-field','',0),(47819,1,'2017-03-05 01:33:30','2017-03-05 01:33:30','a:7:{s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"tab\";s:12:\"instructions\";s:0:\"\";s:8:\"required\";i:0;s:17:\"conditional_logic\";i:0;s:7:\"wrapper\";a:3:{s:5:\"width\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"class\";s:0:\"\";s:2:\"id\";s:0:\"\";}s:9:\"placement\";s:3:\"top\";s:8:\"endpoint\";i:0;}','Video','video','publish','closed','closed','','field_58bb6ad89f5c2','','','2017-03-05 01:33:49','2017-03-05 01:33:49','',47794,'https://redrambles.blog//?post_type=acf-field&#038;p=47819',14,'acf-field','',0),(47820,1,'2017-03-05 01:34:27','2017-03-05 01:34:27','a:7:{s:4:\"type\";s:3:\"tab\";s:12:\"instructions\";s:0:\"\";s:8:\"required\";i:0;s:17:\"conditional_logic\";i:0;s:7:\"wrapper\";a:3:{s:5:\"width\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"class\";s:0:\"\";s:2:\"id\";s:0:\"\";}s:9:\"placement\";s:3:\"top\";s:8:\"endpoint\";i:0;}','Sidebar Text','','publish','closed','closed','','field_58bb6b12bfe25','','','2017-03-05 01:34:27','2017-03-05 01:34:27','',47794,'https://redrambles.blog//?post_type=acf-field&p=47820',17,'acf-field','',0),(47822,1,'2017-03-20 21:32:11','2017-03-20 21:32:11','<iframe width=\"640\" height=\"360\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/O---4sbDtOE\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>\r\n\r\nMove your local project to a staging server using Git and WPEngine.','From local to live screencast','','publish','open','open','','local-to-live','','','2017-05-30 15:32:47','2017-05-30 15:32:47','',0,'https://redrambles.blog//?p=47822',0,'post','',0),(47823,1,'2017-03-20 21:32:02','2017-03-20 21:32:02','https://youtu.be/QH2-TGUlwu4','Test Video post','','inherit','closed','closed','','47822-revision-v1','','','2017-03-20 21:32:02','2017-03-20 21:32:02','',47822,'https://redrambles.blog//47822-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(47824,1,'2017-03-20 21:42:47','2017-03-20 21:42:47','<iframe width=\"400\" height=\"225\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/O---4sbDtOE\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>','Test Video post','','inherit','closed','closed','','47822-revision-v1','','','2017-03-20 21:42:47','2017-03-20 21:42:47','',47822,'https://redrambles.blog//47822-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(47825,1,'2017-03-20 21:44:27','2017-03-20 21:44:27','<iframe width=\"640\" height=\"360\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/O---4sbDtOE\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>','Test Video post','','inherit','closed','closed','','47822-revision-v1','','','2017-03-20 21:44:27','2017-03-20 21:44:27','',47822,'https://redrambles.blog//47822-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(47826,1,'2017-03-20 21:45:31','2017-03-20 21:45:31','<iframe width=\"640\" height=\"360\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/O---4sbDtOE\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>\r\n\r\nMove your local project to a staging server using Git and WPEngine.','Test Video post','','inherit','closed','closed','','47822-revision-v1','','','2017-03-20 21:45:31','2017-03-20 21:45:31','',47822,'https://redrambles.blog//47822-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(47827,1,'2017-03-20 21:46:18','2017-03-20 21:46:18','<iframe width=\"640\" height=\"360\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/O---4sbDtOE\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>\r\n\r\nMove your local project to a staging server using Git and WPEngine.','From local to live screencast','','inherit','closed','closed','','47822-revision-v1','','','2017-03-20 21:46:18','2017-03-20 21:46:18','',47822,'https://redrambles.blog//47822-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(47829,1,'2017-04-15 01:33:35','2017-04-15 01:33:35','<div>\r\n\r\nI’m a student of all things web development and hack away at various code projects with the passion of a zealot. I\'m also a mom of a small pack of minions who will one day do my bidding. (For now, I\'m working on our family grocery shopping time NOT shaving years off of my life.)\r\n\r\nDuring my off-parent duties, when I’m not crafting code (which in fairness - is most of the time), I like to sing, play the mandolin, curl up with a good sci-fi/fantasy book or take long walks with my dogs.\r\n<div class=\"social-btns\">\r\n<div id=\"crayon-58f1781c2e9f2383798104-1\" class=\"crayon-line\"><span class=\"crayon-i\">I</span>’<span class=\"crayon-i\">m</span> <span class=\"crayon-e\">the </span><span class=\"crayon-e\">lead </span><span class=\"crayon-e\">developer </span><span class=\"crayon-v\">at</span> <span class=\"crayon-o\">&lt;</span><span class=\"crayon-i\">a</span> <span class=\"crayon-v\">href</span><span class=\"crayon-o\">=</span><span class=\"crayon-s\">\"http://skillcrush.com\"</span><span class=\"crayon-o\">&gt;</span><span class=\"crayon-v\">Skillcrush</span><span class=\"crayon-o\">&lt;</span><span class=\"crayon-o\">/</span><span class=\"crayon-v\">a</span><span class=\"crayon-o\">&gt;</span> <span class=\"crayon-st\">as</span> <span class=\"crayon-e\">well </span><span class=\"crayon-st\">as</span> <span class=\"crayon-e\">an </span><span class=\"crayon-e\">instructor </span><span class=\"crayon-st\">in</span> <span class=\"crayon-e\">Ruby </span><span class=\"crayon-st\">and</span> <span class=\"crayon-v\">JavaScript</span><span class=\"crayon-sy\">.</span> <span class=\"crayon-i\">I</span> <span class=\"crayon-e\">got </span><span class=\"crayon-e\">my </span><span class=\"crayon-e\">start </span><span class=\"crayon-st\">as</span> <span class=\"crayon-e\">an </span><span class=\"crayon-e\">administrative </span><span class=\"crayon-e\">assistant </span><span class=\"crayon-st\">in</span> <span class=\"crayon-e\">the </span><span class=\"crayon-e\">IT </span><span class=\"crayon-e\">department </span><span class=\"crayon-e\">at </span><span class=\"crayon-e\">the </span><span class=\"crayon-e\">Broad </span><span class=\"crayon-e\">Institute </span><span class=\"crayon-e\">of </span><span class=\"crayon-e\">Harvard </span><span class=\"crayon-st\">and</span> <span class=\"crayon-e\">MIT </span><span class=\"crayon-st\">and</span> <span class=\"crayon-e\">worked </span><span class=\"crayon-e\">my </span><span class=\"crayon-e\">way </span><span class=\"crayon-e\">up </span><span class=\"crayon-st\">to</span> <span class=\"crayon-e\">software </span><span class=\"crayon-v\">engineer</span><span class=\"crayon-o\">!</span></div>\r\n<div id=\"crayon-58f1781c2e9f2383798104-2\" class=\"crayon-line crayon-striped-line\"></div>\r\n<div id=\"crayon-58f1781c2e9f2383798104-3\" class=\"crayon-line\"><span class=\"crayon-i\">When</span> <span class=\"crayon-i\">I</span>’<span class=\"crayon-i\">m</span> <span class=\"crayon-st\">not</span> <span class=\"crayon-e\">at </span><span class=\"crayon-e\">Skillcrush</span> <span class=\"crayon-sy\">(</span><span class=\"crayon-e\">which </span><span class=\"crayon-st\">is</span> <span class=\"crayon-e\">most </span><span class=\"crayon-e\">of </span><span class=\"crayon-e\">the </span><span class=\"crayon-v\">time</span><span class=\"crayon-sy\">)</span><span class=\"crayon-sy\">,</span> <span class=\"crayon-i\">I</span> <span class=\"crayon-e\">can </span><span class=\"crayon-e\">usually </span><span class=\"crayon-e\">be </span><span class=\"crayon-e\">found </span><span class=\"crayon-e\">on </span><span class=\"crayon-e\">my </span><span class=\"crayon-v\">bike</span><span class=\"crayon-sy\">,</span> <span class=\"crayon-e\">practicing </span><span class=\"crayon-v\">French</span><span class=\"crayon-sy\">,</span> <span class=\"crayon-i\">enjoying</span> <span class=\"crayon-i\">a</span> <span class=\"crayon-e\">cocktail </span><span class=\"crayon-e\">at </span><span class=\"crayon-e\">my </span><span class=\"crayon-e\">favorite </span><span class=\"crayon-e\">neighborhood </span><span class=\"crayon-e\">bar </span><span class=\"crayon-st\">or</span> <span class=\"crayon-e\">playing </span><span class=\"crayon-v\">Zelda</span><span class=\"crayon-sy\">.</span></div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>','Hi, I\'m Ann. </br> I love building websites.','','inherit','closed','closed','','4-revision-v1','','','2017-04-15 01:33:35','2017-04-15 01:33:35','',4,'https://redrambles.blog//4-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(47830,1,'2017-04-15 01:34:44','2017-04-15 01:34:44','<div>\r\n\r\nI’m a student of all things web development and hack away at various code projects with the passion of a zealot. I\'m also a mom of a small pack of minions who will one day do my bidding. (For now, I\'m working on our family grocery shopping time NOT shaving years off of my life.)\r\n\r\nDuring my off-parent duties, when I’m not crafting code (which in fairness - is most of the time), I like to sing, play the mandolin, curl up with a good sci-fi/fantasy book or take long walks with my dogs.\r\n<div>\r\n<div id=\"crayon-58f1781c2e9f2383798104-1\">I’m the lead developer at &lt;a href=\"http://skillcrush.com\"&gt;Skillcrush&lt;/a&gt; as well as an instructor in Ruby and JavaScript. I got my start as an administrative assistant in the IT department at the Broad Institute of Harvard and MIT and worked my way up to software engineer!</div>\r\n<div id=\"crayon-58f1781c2e9f2383798104-2\"></div>\r\n<div id=\"crayon-58f1781c2e9f2383798104-3\">When I’m not at Skillcrush (which is most of the time), I can usually be found on my bike, practicing French, enjoying a cocktail at my favorite neighborhood bar or playing Zelda.</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>','Hi, I\'m Ann. </br> I love building websites.','','inherit','closed','closed','','4-revision-v1','','','2017-04-15 01:34:44','2017-04-15 01:34:44','',4,'https://redrambles.blog//4-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(47831,1,'2017-04-15 01:37:06','2017-04-15 01:37:06','<div>\r\n\r\nI’m a student of all things web development and hack away at various code projects with the passion of a zealot. I\'m also a mom of a small pack of minions who will one day do my bidding. (For now, I\'m working on our family grocery shopping time NOT shaving years off of my life.)\r\n\r\nDuring my off-parent duties, when I’m not crafting code (which in fairness - is most of the time), I like to sing, play the mandolin, curl up with a good sci-fi/fantasy book or take long walks with my dogs.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\nI’m the lead developer at &lt;a href=\"http://skillcrush.com\"&gt;Skillcrush&lt;/a&gt; as well as an instructor in Ruby and JavaScript. I got my start as an administrative assistant in the IT department at the Broad Institute of Harvard and MIT and worked my way up to software engineer!\r\n\r\nWhen I’m not at Skillcrush (which is most of the time), I can usually be found on my bike, practicing French, enjoying a cocktail at my favorite neighborhood bar or playing Zelda.','Hi, I\'m Ann. </br> I love building websites.','','inherit','closed','closed','','4-revision-v1','','','2017-04-15 01:37:06','2017-04-15 01:37:06','',4,'https://redrambles.blog//4-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(47832,1,'2017-04-15 01:37:48','2017-04-15 01:37:48','<div>\r\n\r\nI’m a student of all things web development and hack away at various code projects with the passion of a zealot. I\'m also a mom of a small pack of minions who will one day do my bidding. (For now, I\'m working on our family grocery shopping time NOT shaving years off of my life.)\r\n\r\nDuring my off-parent duties, when I’m not crafting code (which in fairness - is most of the time), I like to sing, play the mandolin, curl up with a good sci-fi/fantasy book or take long walks with my dogs.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n','Hi, I\'m Ann. </br> I love building websites.','','inherit','closed','closed','','4-revision-v1','','','2017-04-15 01:37:48','2017-04-15 01:37:48','',4,'https://redrambles.blog//4-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(47834,1,'2017-04-21 14:54:14','2017-04-21 14:54:14','<div>\r\n\r\n<p>I’m a student of all things web development and hack away at various code projects with the passion of a zealot. I\'m also a mom of a small pack of minions who will one day do my bidding. (For now, I\'m working on our family grocery shopping time NOT shaving years off of my life.)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>During my off-parent duties, when I’m not crafting code (which in fairness - is most of the time), I like to sing, play the mandolin, curl up with a good sci-fi/fantasy book or take long walks with my dogs.</p>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n','Hi, I\'m Ann. </br> I love building websites.','','inherit','closed','closed','','4-revision-v1','','','2017-04-21 14:54:14','2017-04-21 14:54:14','',4,'https://redrambles.blog//4-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(47837,1,'2017-05-24 01:44:43','2017-05-24 01:44:43','Sometimes we need our git repositories to NOT track something. We still want that file or directory - but we just want git to pretend it doesn\'t exist.\r\n\r\nWe want git to ignore it.\r\n\r\nThis is not an uncommon request! In fact, it\'s standard practice to group these files / directories together in a specific file which is (perhaps predictably) called the .gitignore.\r\n\r\nHere are two examples of .gitignore files that I will use on WordPress projects - depending on whether or not I am versioning the core files.','These aren\'t the files you are looking for.','','inherit','closed','closed','','47671-revision-v1','','','2017-05-24 01:44:43','2017-05-24 01:44:43','',47671,'https://redrambles.blog//47671-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(47838,1,'2017-05-29 15:39:21','2017-05-29 15:39:21','You have a local project, you\'ve put it under version control and now you want to use Git\'s awesome powers to push all of your files over to your live site - because SFTP blows. Right?! Dreamhost say that they support Git, so I figured - righto - let\'s get this show on the road!\r\n\r\nEhhhhhh - This is where things got murky - at least for me. The documentation I unearthed was incomplete at best. Though Git <strong>is</strong> already installed on my Dreamhost server, that was pretty much the end of git support, at least in so far as I found. (sad emoji)\r\n\r\nSo! I decided to do what I always do in these situations: pour myself a glass of wine, put on some good tunes, crack open my terminal and hack at things until I get the result I\'m after. Once I was successful (yay!) - I put together a neat little list of notes that I will share with you here, to hopefully spare you some unnecessary pain.\r\n\r\n<h5>Step 1</h5>\r\n<strong>SSH into your server.</strong>\r\n<p>This is the first thing. You need to get shell access and be able to log in. The first thing you\'ll see when you log in is this.</p> <img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-47839\" src=\"https://redrambles.blog//wp-content/uploads/2017/05/skymaster.png\" alt=\"skymaster\" width=\"467\" height=\"234\" /> <p>I went around the house saying \'SKYMASTEERRRRRR\' for an hour - bless you if this also brought you joy. Also could have been the wine.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Once you\'ve gotten over the Skymaster thing, you\'ll find that you are in your home directory. You should see a site folder there called \'name-you-picked.dreamhoster.com\' if you are using the temporary domain that you are given when you sign up. If you linked your own domain to Dreamhost - you will see your domain name there \'your-awesome-domain-name.something\'.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>We are going to create another directory to keep our site directory company, called \'repo\' </strong> - and then we will move into it.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n<code>mkdir repo &amp;&amp; cd repo</code>\r\n\r\n<h5>Step 2</h5>\r\nNext, we will <strong>create a new directory called \'sitename.git\' and move into it</strong>. I\'m just going to call mine \'kittens\'.\r\n\r\n<code>mkdir kittens.git &amp;&amp; cd kittens.git</code>\r\n\r\n<h5>Step 3</h5>\r\nNice! Now we need to make this into a bare repository.\r\n\r\n<code>git init --bare</code>\r\n\r\nAnd then move into the \'hooks\' directory:\r\n<code>cd hooks</code>\r\n\r\n\r\nIn this hooks directory, there will be a file called \'post-receive\'. <strong>This is what we are going to use in order to deploy our files on the server.</strong> Essentially, we will tell Git: \"Hey! When you receive a push over here - I want you to take it and deploy the files in my site folder please - k thx!\" (Git replies something like: \"k cool, whatevs\").\r\n\r\nHere\'s what we need to put in that your post-receive file:\r\n\r\n<code>#!/bin/sh\r\ngit --work-tree=/home/your_username/your_site_folder.whatever --git-dir=/home/your_username/repo/kittens.git checkout -f</code>\r\n\r\nYou can use \'nano\' or \'vi\' to launch a terminal based editor in order to enter this line of code (edit the ‘your_username’ to be your actual username and ‘your_site_folder’ oh good grief you know this right!?) and then save the file.\r\n\r\n<h5>Step 4</h5>\r\nNext - we need to <strong>make that post-receive file executable</strong>. It\'s like giving it superpowers.\r\n\r\n\r\n<code>chmod +x post-receive</code>\r\n\r\n<h5>Step 5</h5>\r\nNow you can bail out of the server! Woot! Until we meet again, Skymaster. Until we meet again. Back in your local project, you\'ll need to <strong>add a remote connection</strong> to your site. It will look something like this:\r\n\r\n<code>git remote add dreamhost ssh://your_username@your_site_name.whatever/home/your_username/repo/kittens.git</code>\r\n\r\nI know.\r\n\r\nThen - you\'ll <strong>push up those files</strong>!\r\n\r\n<code>git push dreamhost master</code>\r\n\r\nThen you dance!!!\r\n\r\nThis is only half of the equation, of course - in order to fully migrate your site, you\'ll also need to move over your database - but the point here is, folks - that you can now deploy your file changes using Git instead of stupid SFTP and you will feel like a total badass.\r\n\r\nSKYMASTERRRRRRRRRR!!!','How to deploy with Dreamhost using Git','You have a local project, you\'ve put it under version control and now you want to use Git\'s awesome powers to push all of your files over to your live site - because SFTP blows. ','publish','open','open','','how-to-deploy-with-dreamhost-using-git','','','2017-08-22 15:33:00','2017-08-22 15:33:00','',0,'https://redrambles.blog//?p=47838',0,'post','',1),(47839,1,'2017-05-29 15:00:26','2017-05-29 15:00:26','dreamhost ssh','skymaster','','inherit','open','closed','','skymaster','','','2017-05-29 15:00:38','2017-05-29 15:00:38','',47838,'https://redrambles.blog//wp-content/uploads/2017/05/skymaster.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(47840,1,'2017-05-29 15:09:14','2017-05-29 15:09:14','You have a local project, you\'ve put it under version control and now you want to use Git\'s awesome powers to push all of your files over to your live site - because SFTP blows. Right?! Dreamhost say that they support Git, so I figured - righto - let\'s get this show on the road!\r\n\r\nEhhhhhh - This is where things got murky - at least for me. The documentation I unearthed was incomplete at best. Though Git <strong>is</strong> already installed on my Dreamhost server, that was pretty much the end of git support, at least in so far as I found. (sad emoji)\r\n\r\nSo! I decided to do what I always do in these situations: pour myself a glass of wine, put on some good tunes, crack open my terminal and hack at things until I get the result I\'m after. Once I was successful (yay!) - I put together a neat little list of notes that I will share with you here, to hopefully spare you some unnecessary pain.\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>SSH into your server. \r\nThis is the first thing. You need to get shell access and be able to log in. The first thing you\'ll see when you log in is this. <img src=\"https://redrambles.blog//wp-content/uploads/2017/05/skymaster-300x150.png\" alt=\"skymaster\" width=\"300\" height=\"150\" class=\"alignleft size-medium wp-image-47839\" /> I went around the house saying \'SKYMASTEERRRRRR\' for an hour - bless you if this also brought you joy. Also could have been the wine. </li>\r\n\r\n<li>Once you\'ve gotten over the Skymaster thing, you\'ll find that you are in your home directory. You should see a site folder there called \'name-you-picked.dreamhoster.com\' if you are using the temporary domain that you are given when you sign up. If you linked your own domain to Dreamhost - you will see your domain name there \'your-awesome-domain-name.something\'. We are going to create another directory to keep our site directory company, called \'repo\'. \r\nmkdir repo\r\n</li>\r\n\r\n</li></li>\r\n</ol>','Dreamhost and Git - how to deploy from local to live.','','inherit','closed','closed','','47838-revision-v1','','','2017-05-29 15:09:14','2017-05-29 15:09:14','',47838,'https://redrambles.blog//47838-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(47841,1,'2017-05-29 15:10:14','2017-05-29 15:10:14','You have a local project, you\'ve put it under version control and now you want to use Git\'s awesome powers to push all of your files over to your live site - because SFTP blows. Right?! Dreamhost say that they support Git, so I figured - righto - let\'s get this show on the road!\r\n\r\nEhhhhhh - This is where things got murky - at least for me. The documentation I unearthed was incomplete at best. Though Git <strong>is</strong> already installed on my Dreamhost server, that was pretty much the end of git support, at least in so far as I found. (sad emoji)\r\n\r\nSo! I decided to do what I always do in these situations: pour myself a glass of wine, put on