en move into the \'hooks\' directory:\r\ncd hooks\r\n</li>\r\n<li> \r\nIn this hooks directory, there will be a file called \'post-receive\'. This is what we are going to use in order to deploy our files on the server. Essentially, we will tell Git: \"Hey! When you receive a push over here - I want you to take it and deploy the files in my site folder please - k thx!\" (Git replies something like: \"k cool, whatevs\").\r\n\r\nHere\'s what we need to put in that file:\r\n#!/bin/sh\r\ngit --work-tree=/home/your_username/your_site_folder.whatever --git-dir=/home/your_username/repo/kittens.git checkout -f\r\n\r\nYou can use \'nano\' or \'vi\' to launch a terminal a based editor in order to enter this line of code and then save the file.\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\nNext - we need to make that post-receive file executable. It\'s like giving it superpowers.\r\nchmod +x post-receive\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>','Dreamhost and Git - how to deploy from local to live.','','inherit','closed','closed','','47838-revision-v1','','','2017-05-29 15:23:55','2017-05-29 15:23:55','',47838,'https://redrambles.blog//47838-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(47845,1,'2017-05-29 15:29:32','2017-05-29 15:29:32','You have a local project, you\'ve put it under version control and now you want to use Git\'s awesome powers to push all of your files over to your live site - because SFTP blows. Right?! Dreamhost say that they support Git, so I figured - righto - let\'s get this show on the road!\r\n\r\nEhhhhhh - This is where things got murky - at least for me. The documentation I unearthed was incomplete at best. Though Git <strong>is</strong> already installed on my Dreamhost server, that was pretty much the end of git support, at least in so far as I found. (sad emoji)\r\n\r\nSo! I decided to do what I always do in these situations: pour myself a glass of wine, put on some good tunes, crack open my terminal and hack at things until I get the result I\'m after. Once I was successful (yay!) - I put together a neat little list of notes that I will share with you here, to hopefully spare you some unnecessary pain.\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><h5>SSH into your server.<h5>\r\nThis is the first thing. You need to get shell access and be able to log in. The first thing you\'ll see when you log in is this. <img src=\"https://redrambles.blog//wp-content/uploads/2017/05/skymaster.png\" alt=\"skymaster\" width=\"467\" height=\"234\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-47839\" /> I went around the house saying \'SKYMASTEERRRRRR\' for an hour - bless you if this also brought you joy. Also could have been the wine. </li>\r\n<li>Once you\'ve gotten over the Skymaster thing, you\'ll find that you are in your home directory. You should see a site folder there called \'name-you-picked.dreamhoster.com\' if you are using the temporary domain that you are given when you sign up. If you linked your own domain to Dreamhost - you will see your domain name there \'your-awesome-domain-name.something\'. We are going to create another directory to keep our site directory company, called \'repo\' - and then we will move into it.\r\nmkdir repo && cd repo\r\n</li>\r\n</li>Next, we will create a new directory called \'sitename.git\' and move into it. I\'m just going to call mine \'kittens\'.\r\nmkdir kittens.git && cd kittens.git</li>\r\n<li>Nice! Now we need to make this into a bare repository.\r\ngit init --bare\r\n\r\nAnd then move into the \'hooks\' directory:\r\ncd hooks\r\n</li>\r\n<li> \r\nIn this hooks directory, there will be a file called \'post-receive\'. This is what we are going to use in order to deploy our files on the server. Essentially, we will tell Git: \"Hey! When you receive a push over here - I want you to take it and deploy the files in my site folder please - k thx!\" (Git replies something like: \"k cool, whatevs\").\r\n\r\nHere\'s what we need to put in that file:\r\n#!/bin/sh\r\ngit --work-tree=/home/your_username/your_site_folder.whatever --git-dir=/home/your_username/repo/kittens.git checkout -f\r\n\r\nYou can use \'nano\' or \'vi\' to launch a terminal a based editor in order to enter this line of code and then save the file.\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\nNext - we need to make that post-receive file executable. It\'s like giving it superpowers.\r\nchmod +x post-receive\r\n</li>\r\n<li>Now you can bail out of the server! Woot! Until we meet again, Skymaster. Until we meet again.\r\n\r\nBack in your local project, you\'ll need to add a remote connection to your site. It will look something like this:\r\ngit remote add dreamhost ssh://your_username@your_site_name.wahetever/home/your_username/repo/kittens.git\r\n\r\nI know.\r\n\r\n\r\nThen - you\'ll push up those files!\r\n\r\ngit push dreamhost master\r\n\r\nThen you dance!!!\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\nThis is only half of the equation, of course - in order to fully migrate your site, you\'ll also need to move over your database - but the point here is, folks - that you can now deploy your file changes using Git instead of stupid SFTP and you will feel like a total badass.\r\n\r\nSKYMASTERRRRRRRRRR!!!','Dreamhost and Git - how to deploy from local to live.','','inherit','closed','closed','','47838-revision-v1','','','2017-05-29 15:29:32','2017-05-29 15:29:32','',47838,'https://redrambles.blog//47838-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(47846,1,'2017-05-29 15:30:27','2017-05-29 15:30:27','You have a local project, you\'ve put it under version control and now you want to use Git\'s awesome powers to push all of your files over to your live site - because SFTP blows. Right?! Dreamhost say that they support Git, so I figured - righto - let\'s get this show on the road!\r\n\r\nEhhhhhh - This is where things got murky - at least for me. The documentation I unearthed was incomplete at best. Though Git <strong>is</strong> already installed on my Dreamhost server, that was pretty much the end of git support, at least in so far as I found. (sad emoji)\r\n\r\nSo! I decided to do what I always do in these situations: pour myself a glass of wine, put on some good tunes, crack open my terminal and hack at things until I get the result I\'m after. Once I was successful (yay!) - I put together a neat little list of notes that I will share with you here, to hopefully spare you some unnecessary pain.\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><h5>SSH into your server.<h5>\r\nThis is the first thing. You need to get shell access and be able to log in. The first thing you\'ll see when you log in is this. <img src=\"https://redrambles.blog//wp-content/uploads/2017/05/skymaster.png\" alt=\"skymaster\" width=\"467\" height=\"234\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-47839\" /> I went around the house saying \'SKYMASTEERRRRRR\' for an hour - bless you if this also brought you joy. Also could have been the wine. </li>\r\n<li>Once you\'ve gotten over the Skymaster thing, you\'ll find that you are in your home directory. You should see a site folder there called \'name-you-picked.dreamhoster.com\' if you are using the temporary domain that you are given when you sign up. If you linked your own domain to Dreamhost - you will see your domain name there \'your-awesome-domain-name.something\'. We are going to create another directory to keep our site directory company, called \'repo\' - and then we will move into it.\r\n<code>mkdir repo && cd repo</code>\r\n</li>\r\n</li>Next, we will create a new directory called \'sitename.git\' and move into it. I\'m just going to call mine \'kittens\'.\r\nmkdir kittens.git && cd kittens.git</li>\r\n<li>Nice! Now we need to make this into a bare repository.\r\ngit init --bare\r\n\r\nAnd then move into the \'hooks\' directory:\r\ncd hooks\r\n</li>\r\n<li> \r\nIn this hooks directory, there will be a file called \'post-receive\'. This is what we are going to use in order to deploy our files on the server. Essentially, we will tell Git: \"Hey! When you receive a push over here - I want you to take it and deploy the files in my site folder please - k thx!\" (Git replies something like: \"k cool, whatevs\").\r\n\r\nHere\'s what we need to put in that file:\r\n#!/bin/sh\r\ngit --work-tree=/home/your_username/your_site_folder.whatever --git-dir=/home/your_username/repo/kittens.git checkout -f\r\n\r\nYou can use \'nano\' or \'vi\' to launch a terminal a based editor in order to enter this line of code and then save the file.\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\nNext - we need to make that post-receive file executable. It\'s like giving it superpowers.\r\nchmod +x post-receive\r\n</li>\r\n<li>Now you can bail out of the server! Woot! Until we meet again, Skymaster. Until we meet again.\r\n\r\nBack in your local project, you\'ll need to add a remote connection to your site. It will look something like this:\r\ngit remote add dreamhost ssh://your_username@your_site_name.wahetever/home/your_username/repo/kittens.git\r\n\r\nI know.\r\n\r\n\r\nThen - you\'ll push up those files!\r\n\r\ngit push dreamhost master\r\n\r\nThen you dance!!!\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\nThis is only half of the equation, of course - in order to fully migrate your site, you\'ll also need to move over your database - but the point here is, folks - that you can now deploy your file changes using Git instead of stupid SFTP and you will feel like a total badass.\r\n\r\nSKYMASTERRRRRRRRRR!!!','Dreamhost and Git - how to deploy from local to live.','','inherit','closed','closed','','47838-revision-v1','','','2017-05-29 15:30:27','2017-05-29 15:30:27','',47838,'https://redrambles.blog//47838-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(47847,1,'2017-05-29 15:33:27','2017-05-29 15:33:27','You have a local project, you\'ve put it under version control and now you want to use Git\'s awesome powers to push all of your files over to your live site - because SFTP blows. Right?! Dreamhost say that they support Git, so I figured - righto - let\'s get this show on the road!\r\n\r\nEhhhhhh - This is where things got murky - at least for me. The documentation I unearthed was incomplete at best. Though Git <strong>is</strong> already installed on my Dreamhost server, that was pretty much the end of git support, at least in so far as I found. (sad emoji)\r\n\r\nSo! I decided to do what I always do in these situations: pour myself a glass of wine, put on some good tunes, crack open my terminal and hack at things until I get the result I\'m after. Once I was successful (yay!) - I put together a neat little list of notes that I will share with you here, to hopefully spare you some unnecessary pain.\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><h5>SSH into your server.<h5>\r\nThis is the first thing. You need to get shell access and be able to log in. The first thing you\'ll see when you log in is this. <img src=\"https://redrambles.blog//wp-content/uploads/2017/05/skymaster.png\" alt=\"skymaster\" width=\"467\" height=\"234\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-47839\" /> I went around the house saying \'SKYMASTEERRRRRR\' for an hour - bless you if this also brought you joy. Also could have been the wine. </li>\r\n<li>Once you\'ve gotten over the Skymaster thing, you\'ll find that you are in your home directory. You should see a site folder there called \'name-you-picked.dreamhoster.com\' if you are using the temporary domain that you are given when you sign up. If you linked your own domain to Dreamhost - you will see your domain name there \'your-awesome-domain-name.something\'. We are going to create another directory to keep our site directory company, called \'repo\' - and then we will move into it.\r\n<code>mkdir repo && cd repo</code>\r\n</li>\r\n</li>Next, we will create a new directory called \'sitename.git\' and move into it. I\'m just going to call mine \'kittens\'.\r\nmkdir kittens.git && cd kittens.git</li>\r\n<li>Nice! Now we need to make this into a bare repository.\r\n<code>git init --bare</code>\r\n\r\nAnd then move into the \'hooks\' directory:\r\n<code>cd hooks</code>\r\n</li>\r\n<li> \r\nIn this hooks directory, there will be a file called \'post-receive\'. This is what we are going to use in order to deploy our files on the server. Essentially, we will tell Git: \"Hey! When you receive a push over here - I want you to take it and deploy the files in my site folder please - k thx!\" (Git replies something like: \"k cool, whatevs\").\r\n\r\nHere\'s what we need to put in that file:\r\n<code>#!/bin/sh\r\ngit --work-tree=/home/your_username/your_site_folder.whatever --git-dir=/home/your_username/repo/kittens.git checkout -f</code>\r\n\r\nYou can use \'nano\' or \'vi\' to launch a terminal a based editor in order to enter this line of code and then save the file.\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\nNext - we need to make that post-receive file executable. It\'s like giving it superpowers.\r\n\r\n<code>chmod +x post-receive</code>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>Now you can bail out of the server! Woot! Until we meet again, Skymaster. Until we meet again.\r\n\r\nBack in your local project, you\'ll need to add a remote connection to your site. It will look something like this:\r\n\r\n<code>git remote add dreamhost ssh://your_username@your_site_name.wahetever/home/your_username/repo/kittens.git</code>\r\n\r\nI know.\r\n\r\n\r\nThen - you\'ll push up those files!\r\n\r\n<code>git push dreamhost master</code>\r\n\r\nThen you dance!!!\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\nThis is only half of the equation, of course - in order to fully migrate your site, you\'ll also need to move over your database - but the point here is, folks - that you can now deploy your file changes using Git instead of stupid SFTP and you will feel like a total badass.\r\n\r\nSKYMASTERRRRRRRRRR!!!','Dreamhost and Git - how to deploy from local to live.','','inherit','closed','closed','','47838-revision-v1','','','2017-05-29 15:33:27','2017-05-29 15:33:27','',47838,'https://redrambles.blog//47838-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(47848,1,'2017-05-29 15:36:38','2017-05-29 15:36:38','You have a local project, you\'ve put it under version control and now you want to use Git\'s awesome powers to push all of your files over to your live site - because SFTP blows. Right?! Dreamhost say that they support Git, so I figured - righto - let\'s get this show on the road!\r\n\r\nEhhhhhh - This is where things got murky - at least for me. The documentation I unearthed was incomplete at best. Though Git <strong>is</strong> already installed on my Dreamhost server, that was pretty much the end of git support, at least in so far as I found. (sad emoji)\r\n\r\nSo! I decided to do what I always do in these situations: pour myself a glass of wine, put on some good tunes, crack open my terminal and hack at things until I get the result I\'m after. Once I was successful (yay!) - I put together a neat little list of notes that I will share with you here, to hopefully spare you some unnecessary pain.\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>SSH into your server.</strong>\r\nThis is the first thing. You need to get shell access and be able to log in. The first thing you\'ll see when you log in is this. <img src=\"https://redrambles.blog//wp-content/uploads/2017/05/skymaster.png\" alt=\"skymaster\" width=\"467\" height=\"234\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-47839\" /> I went around the house saying \'SKYMASTEERRRRRR\' for an hour - bless you if this also brought you joy. Also could have been the wine. </li>\r\n\r\n<li>Once you\'ve gotten over the Skymaster thing, you\'ll find that you are in your home directory. You should see a site folder there called \'name-you-picked.dreamhoster.com\' if you are using the temporary domain that you are given when you sign up. If you linked your own domain to Dreamhost - you will see your domain name there \'your-awesome-domain-name.something\'. <strong>We are going to create another directory to keep our site directory company, called \'repo\' - and then we will move into it.</strong>\r\n<code>mkdir repo && cd repo</code>\r\n</li>\r\n</li>Next, we will <strong>create a new directory called \'sitename.git\' and move into it</strong>. I\'m just going to call mine \'kittens\'.\r\nmkdir kittens.git && cd kittens.git</li>\r\n<li>Nice! Now we need to make this into a bare repository.\r\n<code>git init --bare</code>\r\n\r\nAnd then move into the \'hooks\' directory:\r\n<code>cd hooks</code>\r\n</li>\r\n<li> \r\nIn this hooks directory, there will be a file called \'post-receive\'. This is what we are going to use in order to deploy our files on the server. Essentially, we will tell Git: \"Hey! When you receive a push over here - I want you to take it and deploy the files in my site folder please - k thx!\" (Git replies something like: \"k cool, whatevs\").\r\n\r\nHere\'s what we need to put in that file:\r\n<code>#!/bin/sh\r\ngit --work-tree=/home/your_username/your_site_folder.whatever --git-dir=/home/your_username/repo/kittens.git checkout -f</code>\r\n\r\nYou can use \'nano\' or \'vi\' to launch a terminal a based editor in order to enter this line of code and then save the file.\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\nNext - we need to make that post-receive file executable. It\'s like giving it superpowers.\r\n\r\n<code>chmod +x post-receive</code>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>Now you can bail out of the server! Woot! Until we meet again, Skymaster. Until we meet again.\r\n\r\nBack in your local project, you\'ll need to add a remote connection to your site. It will look something like this:\r\n\r\n<code>git remote add dreamhost ssh://your_username@your_site_name.wahetever/home/your_username/repo/kittens.git</code>\r\n\r\nI know.\r\n\r\n\r\nThen - you\'ll push up those files!\r\n\r\n<code>git push dreamhost master</code>\r\n\r\nThen you dance!!!\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\nThis is only half of the equation, of course - in order to fully migrate your site, you\'ll also need to move over your database - but the point here is, folks - that you can now deploy your file changes using Git instead of stupid SFTP and you will feel like a total badass.\r\n\r\nSKYMASTERRRRRRRRRR!!!','Dreamhost and Git - how to deploy from local to live.','','inherit','closed','closed','','47838-revision-v1','','','2017-0