ite_name.wahetever/home/your_username/repo/kittens.git</code>\r\n\r\nI know.\r\n\r\nThen - you\'ll <strong>push up those files</strong>!\r\n\r\n<code>git push dreamhost master</code>\r\n\r\nThen you dance!!!</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThis is only half of the equation, of course - in order to fully migrate your site, you\'ll also need to move over your database - but the point here is, folks - that you can now deploy your file changes using Git instead of stupid SFTP and you will feel like a total badass.\r\n\r\nSKYMASTERRRRRRRRRR!!!','Dreamhost and Git - how to deploy from local to live.','You have a local project, you\'ve put it under version control and now you want to use Git\'s awesome powers to push all of your files over to your live site - because SFTP blows. Right?! Dreamhost say that they support Git, so I figured - righto - let\'s get this show on the road!\r\n\r\nEhhhhhh - This is where things got murky - at least for me. The documentation I unearthed was incomplete at best. Though Git <strong>is</strong> already installed on my Dreamhost server, that was pretty much the end of git support, at least in so far as I found. (sad emoji)\r\n\r\nSo! I decided to do what I always do in these situations: pour myself a glass of wine, put on some good tunes, crack open my terminal and hack at things until I get the result I\'m after. Once I was successful (yay!) - I put together a neat little list of notes that I will share with you here, to hopefully spare you some unnecessary pain.','inherit','closed','closed','','47838-revision-v1','','','2017-05-29 16:31:13','2017-05-29 16:31:13','',47838,'https://redrambles.blog//47838-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(47854,1,'2017-05-29 16:33:24','2017-05-29 16:33:24','a:7:{s:8:\"location\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"param\";s:9:\"post_type\";s:8:\"operator\";s:2:\"==\";s:5:\"value\";s:4:\"post\";}}}s:8:\"position\";s:4:\"side\";s:5:\"style\";s:7:\"default\";s:15:\"label_placement\";s:3:\"top\";s:21:\"instruction_placement\";s:5:\"label\";s:14:\"hide_on_screen\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"description\";s:0:\"\";}','First Excerpt on Blog Page','first-excerpt-on-blog-page','publish','closed','closed','','group_592c4cdda8a05','','','2017-05-29 16:39:26','2017-05-29 16:39:26','',0,'https://redrambles.blog//?post_type=acf-field-group&#038;p=47854',0,'acf-field-group','',0),(47855,1,'2017-05-29 16:33:24','2017-05-29 16:33:24','a:12:{s:4:\"type\";s:5:\"radio\";s:12:\"instructions\";s:156:\"By default, the first blog post on the blog page is shown in full. If this is a particularly long post and you\'d rather only the excerpt show - check \'yes\'.\";s:8:\"required\";i:0;s:17:\"conditional_logic\";i:0;s:7:\"wrapper\";a:3:{s:5:\"width\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"class\";s:0:\"\";s:2:\"id\";s:0:\"\";}s:7:\"choices\";a:2:{s:3:\"yes\";s:3:\"yes\";s:2:\"no\";s:2:\"no\";}s:10:\"allow_null\";i:0;s:12:\"other_choice\";i:0;s:17:\"save_other_choice\";i:0;s:13:\"default_value\";s:2:\"no\";s:6:\"layout\";s:8:\"vertical\";s:13:\"return_format\";s:5:\"value\";}','Show Excerpt?','show_excerpt','publish','closed','closed','','field_592c4cff72e2c','','','2017-05-29 16:37:15','2017-05-29 16:37:15','',47854,'https://redrambles.blog//?post_type=acf-field&#038;p=47855',0,'acf-field','',0),(47856,1,'2017-05-29 16:37:04','2017-05-29 16:37:04','You have a local project, you\'ve put it under version control and now you want to use Git\'s awesome powers to push all of your files over to your live site - because SFTP blows. Right?! Dreamhost say that they support Git, so I figured - righto - let\'s get this show on the road!\r\n\r\nEhhhhhh - This is where things got murky - at least for me. The documentation I unearthed was incomplete at best. Though Git <strong>is</strong> already installed on my Dreamhost server, that was pretty much the end of git support, at least in so far as I found. (sad emoji)\r\n\r\nSo! I decided to do what I always do in these situations: pour myself a glass of wine, put on some good tunes, crack open my terminal and hack at things until I get the result I\'m after. Once I was successful (yay!) - I put together a neat little list of notes that I will share with you here, to hopefully spare you some unnecessary pain.\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li style=\"list-style-type: none;\">\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li><strong>SSH into your server.</strong>\r\nThis is the first thing. You need to get shell access and be able to log in. The first thing you\'ll see when you log in is this. <img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-47839\" src=\"https://redrambles.blog//wp-content/uploads/2017/05/skymaster.png\" alt=\"skymaster\" width=\"467\" height=\"234\" /> I went around the house saying \'SKYMASTEERRRRRR\' for an hour - bless you if this also brought you joy. Also could have been the wine.</li>\r\n\r\n 	<li>Once you\'ve gotten over the Skymaster thing, you\'ll find that you are in your home directory. You should see a site folder there called \'name-you-picked.dreamhoster.com\' if you are using the temporary domain that you are given when you sign up. If you linked your own domain to Dreamhost - you will see your domain name there \'your-awesome-domain-name.something\'. <strong>We are going to create another directory to keep our site directory company, called \'repo\' - and then we will move into it.\r\n</strong>\r\n\r\n<code>mkdir repo &amp;&amp; cd repo</code></li>\r\n\r\n<li>Next, we will <strong>create a new directory called \'sitename.git\' and move into it</strong>. I\'m just going to call mine \'kittens\'.\r\n\r\n<code>mkdir kittens.git &amp;&amp; cd kittens.git</code>\r\n</li>\r\n\r\n<li>Nice! Now we need to make this into a bare repository.\r\n\r\n<code>git init --bare</code>\r\n\r\nAnd then move into the \'hooks\' directory:\r\n<code>cd hooks</code>\r\n</li>\r\n\r\n<li>In this hooks directory, there will be a file called \'post-receive\'. <strong>This is what we are going to use in order to deploy our files on the server.</strong> Essentially, we will tell Git: \"Hey! When you receive a push over here - I want you to take it and deploy the files in my site folder please - k thx!\" (Git replies something like: \"k cool, whatevs\").\r\n\r\nHere\'s what we need to put in that your post-receive file:\r\n\r\n<code>#!/bin/sh\r\ngit --work-tree=/home/your_username/your_site_folder.whatever --git-dir=/home/your_username/repo/kittens.git checkout -f</code>\r\n\r\nYou can use \'nano\' or \'vi\' to launch a terminal a based editor in order to enter this line of code and then save the file.</li>\r\n\r\n<li>Next - we need to <strong>make that post-receive file executable</strong>. It\'s like giving it superpowers.</li>\r\n\r\n\r\n<code>chmod +x post-receive</code>\r\n\r\n 	<li>Now you can bail out of the server! Woot! Until we meet again, Skymaster. Until we meet again.Back in your local project, you\'ll need to <strong>add a remote connection</strong> to your site. It will look something like this:\r\n\r\n<code>git remote add dreamhost ssh://your_username@your_site_name.wahetever/home/your_username/repo/kittens.git</code>\r\n\r\nI know.\r\n\r\nThen - you\'ll <strong>push up those files</strong>!\r\n\r\n<code>git push dreamhost master</code>\r\n\r\nThen you dance!!!</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThis is only half of the equation, of course - in order to fully migrate your site, you\'ll also need to move over your database - but the point here is, folks - that you can now deploy your file changes using Git instead of stupid SFTP and you will feel like a total badass.\r\n\r\nSKYMASTERRRRRRRRRR!!!','Dreamhost and Git - how to deploy from local to live.','You have a local project, you\'ve put it under version control and now you want to use Git\'s awesome powers to push all of your files over to your live site - because SFTP blows. Right?! Dreamhost say that they support Git, so I figured - righto - let\'s get this show on the road!\r\n\r\nEhhhhhh - This is where things got murky - at least for me. The documentation I unearthed was incomplete at best. Though Git <strong>is</strong> already installed on my Dreamhost server, that was pretty much the end of git support, at least in so far as I found. (sad emoji)\r\n\r\nSo! I decided to do what I always do in these situations: pour myself a glass of wine, put on some good tunes, crack open my terminal and hack at things until I get the result I\'m after. Once I was successful (yay!) - I put together a neat little list of notes that I will share with you here, to hopefully spare you some unnecessary pain.','inherit','closed','closed','','47838-revision-v1','','','2017-05-29 16:37:04','2017-05-29 16:37:04','',47838,'https://redrambles.blog//47838-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(47857,1,'2017-05-29 16:42:50','2017-05-29 16:42:50','You have a local project, you\'ve put it under version control and now you want to use Git\'s awesome powers to push all of your files over to your live site - because SFTP blows. Right?! Dreamhost say that they support Git, so I figured - righto - let\'s get this show on the road!\r\n\r\nEhhhhhh - This is where things got murky - at least for me. The documentation I unearthed was incomplete at best. Though Git <strong>is</strong> already installed on my Dreamhost server, that was pretty much the end of git support, at least in so far as I found. (sad emoji)\r\n\r\nSo! I decided to do what I always do in these situations: pour myself a glass of wine, put on some good tunes, crack open my terminal and hack at things until I get the result I\'m after. Once I was successful (yay!) - I put together a neat little list of notes that I will share with you here, to hopefully spare you some unnecessary pain.\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li style=\"list-style-type: none;\">\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li><strong>SSH into your server.</strong>\r\nThis is the first thing. You need to get shell access and be able to log in. The first thing you\'ll see when you log in is this. <img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-47839\" src=\"https://redrambles.blog//wp-content/uploads/2017/05/skymaster.png\" alt=\"skymaster\" width=\"467\" height=\"234\" /> I went around the house saying \'SKYMASTEERRRRRR\' for an hour - bless you if this also brought you joy. Also could have been the wine.</li>\r\n\r\n 	<li>Once you\'ve gotten over the Skymaster thing, you\'ll find that you are in your home directory. You should see a site folder there called \'name-you-picked.dreamhoster.com\' if you are using the temporary domain that you are given when you sign up. If you linked your own domain to Dreamhost - you will see your domain name there \'your-awesome-domain-name.something\'. <strong>We are going to create another directory to keep our site directory company, called \'repo\' - and then we will move into it.\r\n</strong>\r\n\r\n<code>mkdir repo &amp;&amp; cd repo</code></li>\r\n\r\n<li>Next, we will <strong>create a new directory called \'sitename.git\' and move into it</strong>. I\'m just going to call mine \'kittens\'.\r\n\r\n<code>mkdir kittens.git &amp;&amp; cd kittens.git</code>\r\n</li>\r\n\r\n<li>Nice! Now we need to make this into a bare repository.\r\n\r\n<code>git init --bare</code>\r\n\r\nAnd then move into the \'hooks\' directory:\r\n<code>cd hooks</code>\r\n</li>\r\n\r\n<li>In this hooks directory, there will be a file called \'post-receive\'. <strong>This is what we are going to use in order to deploy our files on the server.</strong> Essentially, we will tell Git: \"Hey! When you receive a push over here - I want you to take it and deploy the files in my site folder please - k thx!\" (Git replies something like: \"k cool, whatevs\").\r\n\r\nHere\'s what we need to put in that your post-receive file:\r\n\r\n<code>#!/bin/sh\r\ngit --work-tree=/home/your_username/your_site_folder.whatever --git-dir=/home/your_username/repo/kittens.git checkout -f</code>\r\n\r\nYou can use \'nano\' or \'vi\' to launch a terminal a based editor in order to enter this line of code and then save the file.</li>\r\n\r\n<li>Next - we need to <strong>make that post-receive file executable</strong>. It\'s like giving it superpowers.</li>\r\n\r\n\r\n<code>chmod +x post-receive</code>\r\n\r\n 	<li>Now you can bail out of the server! Woot! Until we meet again, Skymaster. Until we meet again.Back in your local project, you\'ll need to <strong>add a remote connection</strong> to your site. It will look something like this:\r\n\r\n<code>git remote add dreamhost ssh://your_username@your_site_name.wahetever/home/your_username/repo/kittens.git</code>\r\n\r\nI know.\r\n\r\nThen - you\'ll <strong>push up those files</strong>!\r\n\r\n<code>git push dreamhost master</code>\r\n\r\nThen you dance!!!</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThis is only half of the equation, of course - in order to fully migrate your site, you\'ll also need to move over your database - but the point here is, folks - that you can now deploy your file changes using Git instead of stupid SFTP and you will feel like a total badass.\r\n\r\nSKYMASTERRRRRRRRRR!!!','Dreamhost and Git - how to deploy from local to live.','You have a local project, you\'ve put it under version control and now you want to use Git\'s awesome powers to push all of your files over to your live site - because SFTP blows. ','inherit','closed','closed','','47838-revision-v1','','','2017-05-29 16:42:50','2017-05-29 16:42:50','',47838,'https://redrambles.blog//47838-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(47858,1,'2017-05-29 18:37:56','2017-05-29 18:37:56','You have a local project, you\'ve put it under version control and now you want to use Git\'s awesome powers to push all of your files over to your live site - because SFTP blows. Right?! Dreamhost say that they support Git, so I figured - righto - let\'s get this show on the road!\r\n\r\nEhhhhhh - This is where things got murky - at least for me. The documentation I unearthed was incomplete at best. Though Git <strong>is</strong> already installed on my Dreamhost server, that was pretty much the end of git support, at least in so far as I found. (sad emoji)\r\n\r\nSo! I decided to do what I always do in these situations: pour myself a glass of wine, put on some good tunes, crack open my terminal and hack at things until I get the result I\'m after. Once I was successful (yay!) - I put together a neat little list of notes that I will share with you here, to hopefully spare you some unnecessary pain.\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li style=\"list-style-type: none;\">\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li><strong>SSH into your server.</strong>\r\nThis is the first thing. You need to get shell access and be able to log in. The first thing you\'ll see when you log in is this. <img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-47839\" src=\"https://redrambles.blog//wp-content/uploads/2017/05/skymaster.png\" alt=\"skymaster\" width=\"467\" height=\"234\" /> I went around the house saying \'SKYMASTEERRRRRR\' for an hour - bless you if this also brought you joy. Also could have been the wine.</li>\r\n\r\n 	<li>Once you\'ve gotten over the Skymaster thing, you\'ll find that you are in your home directory. You should see a site folder there called \'name-you-picked.dreamhoster.com\' if you are using the temporary domain that you are given when you sign up. If you linked your own domain to Dreamhost - you will see your domain name there \'your-awesome-domain-name.something\'. <strong>We are going to create another directory to keep our site directory company, called \'repo\' - and then we will move into it.\r\n</strong>\r\n\r\n<code>mkdir repo &amp;&amp; cd repo</code></li>\r\n\r\n<li>Next, we will <strong>create a new directory called \'sitename.git\' and move into it</strong>. I\'m just going to call mine \'kittens\'.\r\n\r\n<code>mkdir kittens.git &amp;&amp; cd kittens.git</code>\r\n</li>\r\n\r\n<li>Nice! Now we need to make this into a bare repository.\r\n\r\n<code>git init --bare</code>\r\n\r\nAnd then move into the \'hooks\' directory:\r\n<code>cd hooks</code>\r\n</li>\r\n\r\n<li>In this hooks directory, there will be a file called \'post-receive\'. <strong>This is what we are going to use in order to deploy our files on the server.</strong> Essentially, we will tell Git: \"Hey! When you receive a push over here - I want you to take it and deploy the files in my site folder please - k thx!\" (Git replies something like: \"k cool, whatevs\").\r\n\r\nHere\'s what we need to put in that your post-receive file:\r\n\r\n<code>#!/bin/sh\r\ngit --work-tree=/home/your_username/your_site_folder.whatever --git-dir=/home/your_username/repo/kittens.git checkout -f</code>\r\n\r\nYou can use \'nano\' or \'vi\' to launch a terminal a based editor in order to enter this line of code and then save the file. (edit the ‘your_username’ to be your actual username and ‘your_site_folder’ oh good grief you know this right!?)</li>\r\n\r\n<li>Next - we need to <strong>make that post-receive file executable</strong>. It\'s like giving it superpowers.</li>\r\n\r\n\r\n<code>chmod +x post-receive</code>\r\n\r\n 	<li>Now you can bail out of the server! Woot! Until we meet again, Skymaster. Until we meet again. Back in your local project, you\'ll need to <strong>add a remote connection</strong> to your site. It will look something like this:\r\n\r\n<code>git remote add dreamhost ssh://your_username@your_site_name.wahetever/home/your_username/repo/kittens.git</code>\r\n\r\nI know.\r\n\r\nThen - you\'ll <strong>push up those files</strong>!\r\n\r\n<code>git push dreamhost master</code>\r\n\r\nThen you dance!!!</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThis is only half of the equation, of course - in order to fully migrate your site, you\'ll also need to move over your database - but the point here is, folks - that you can now deploy your file changes using Git instead of stupid SFTP and you will feel like a total badass.\r\n\r\nSKYMASTERRRRRRRRRR!!!','Dreamhost and Git - how to deploy from local to live.','You have a local project, you\'ve put it under version control and now you want to use Git\'s awesome powers to push all of your files over to your live site - because SFTP blows. ','inherit','closed','closed','','47838-revision-v1','','','2017-05-29 18:37:56','2017-05-29 18:37:56','',47838,'https://redrambles.blog//47838-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(47859,1,'2017-05-29 18:38:23','2017-05-29 18:38:23','You have a local project, you\'ve put it under version control and now you want to use Git\'s awesome powers to push all of your files over to your live site - because SFTP blows. Right?! Dreamhost say that they support Git, so I figured - righto - let\'s get this show on the road!\r\n\r\nEhhhhhh - This is where things got murky - at least for me. The documentation I unearthed was incomplete at best. Though Git <strong>is</strong> already installed on my Dreamhost server, that was pretty much the end of git support, at least in so far as I found. (sad emoji)\r\n\r\nSo! I decided to do what I always do in these situations: pour myself a glass of wine, put on some good tunes, crack open my terminal and hack at things until I get the result I\'m after. Once I was successful (yay!) - I put together a neat little list of notes that I will share with you here, to hopefully spare you some unnecessary pain.\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li style=\"list-style-type: none;\">\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li><strong>SSH into your server.</strong>\r\nThis is the first thing. You need to get shell access and be able to log in. The first thing you\'ll see when you log in is this. <img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-47839\" src=\"https://redrambles.blog//wp-content/uploads/2017/05/skymaster.png\" alt=\"skymaster\" width=\"467\" height=\"234\" /> I went around the house saying \'SKYMASTEERRRRRR\' for an hour - bless you if this also brought you joy. Also could have been the wine.</li>\r\n\r\n 	<li>Once you\'ve gotten over the Skymaster thing, you\'ll find that you are in your home directory. You should see a site folder there called \'name-you-picked.dreamhoster.com\' if you are using the temporary domain that you are given when you sign up. If you linked your own domain to Dreamhost - you will see your domain name there \'your-awesome-domain-name.something\'. <strong>We are going to create another directory to keep our site directory company, called \'repo\' - and then we will move into it.\r\n</strong>\r\n\r\n<code>mkdir repo &amp;&amp; cd repo</code></li>\r\n\r\n<li>Next, we will <strong>create a new directory called \'sitename.git\' and move into it</strong>. I\'m just going to call mine \'kittens\'.\r\n\r\n<code>mkdir kittens.git &amp;&amp; cd kittens.git</code>\r\n</li>\r\n\r\n<li>Nice! Now we need to make this into a bare repository.\r\n\r\n<code>git init --bare</code>\r\n\r\nAnd then move into the \'hooks\' directory:\r\n<code>cd hooks</code>\r\n</li>\r\n\r\n<li>In this hooks directory, there will be a file called \'post-receive\'. <strong>This is what we are going to use in order to deploy our files on the server.</strong> Essentially, we will tell Git: \"Hey! When you receive a push over here - I want you to take it and deploy the files in my site folder please - k thx!\" (Git replies something like: \"k cool, whatevs\").\r\n\r\nHere\'s what we need to put in that your post-receive file:\r\n\r\n<code>#!/bin/sh\r\ngit --work-tree=/home/your_username/your_site_folder.whatever --git-dir=/home/your_username/repo/kittens.git checkout -f</code>\r\n\r\nYou can use \'nano\' or \'vi\' to launch a terminal a based editor in order to enter this line of code (edit the ‘your_username’ to be your actual username and ‘your_site_folder’ oh good grief you know this right!?) and then save the file.</li>\r\n\r\n<li>Next - we need to <strong>make that post-receive file executable</strong>. It\'s like giving it superpowers.</li>\r\n\r\n\r\n<code>chmod +x post-receive</code>\r\n\r\n 	<li>Now you can bail out of the server! Woot! Until we meet again, Skymaster. Until we meet again. Back in your local project, you\'ll need to <strong>add a remote connection</strong> to your site. It will look something like this:\r\n\r\n<code>git remote add dreamhost ssh://your_username@your_site_name.wahetever/home/your_username/repo/kittens.git</code>\r\n\r\nI know.\r\n\r\nThen - you\'ll <strong>push up those files</strong>!\r\n\r\n<code>git push dreamhost master</code>\r\n\r\nThen you dance!!!</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThis is only half of the equation, of course - in order to fully migrate your site, you\'ll also need to move over your database - but the point here is, folks - that you can now deploy your file changes using Git instead of stupid SFTP and you will feel like a total badass.\r\n\r\nSKYMASTERRRRRRRRRR!!!','Dreamhost and Git - how to deploy from local to live.','You have a local project, you\'ve put it under version control and now you want to use Git\'s awesome powers to push all of your files over to your live site - because SFTP blows. ','inherit','closed','closed','','47838-revision-v1','','','2017-05-29 18:38:23','2017-05-29 18:38:23','',47838,'https://redrambles.blog//47838-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(47860,1,'2017-05-30 14:31:27','2017-05-30 14:31:27','You have a local project, you\'ve put it under version control and now you want to use Git\'s awesome powers to push all of your files over to your live site - because SFTP blows. Right?! Dreamhost say that they support Git, so I figured - righto - let\'s get this show on the road!\r\n\r\nEhhhhhh - This is where things got murky - at least for me. The documentation I unearthed was incomplete at best. Though Git <strong>is</strong> already installed on my Dreamhost server, that was pretty much the end of git support, at least in so far as I found. (sad emoji)\r\n\r\nSo! I decided to do what I always do in these situations: pour myself a glass of wine, put on some good tunes, crack open my terminal and hack at things until I get the result I\'m after. Once I was successful (yay!) - I put together a neat little list of notes that I will share with you here, to hopefully spare you some unnecessary pain.\r\n\r\n<h5>Step 1</h5>\r\n<strong>SSH into your server.</strong>\r\nThis is the first thing. You need to get shell access and be able to log in. The first thing you\'ll see when you log in is this. <img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-47839\" src=\"https://redrambles.blog//wp-content/uploads/2017/05/skymaster.png\" alt=\"skymaster\" width=\"467\" height=\"234\" /> I went around the house saying \'SKYMASTEERRRRRR\' for an hour - bless you if this also brought you joy. Also could have been the wine.\r\n\r\n Once you\'ve gotten over the Skymaster thing, you\'ll find that you are in your home directory. You should see a site folder there called \'name-you-picked.dreamhoster.com\' if you are using the temporary domain that you are given when you sign up. If you linked your own domain to Dreamhost - you will see your domain name there \'your-awesome-domain-name.something\'. <strong>We are going to create another directory to keep our site directory company, called \'repo\' - and then we will move into it.\r\n</strong>\r\n\r\n<code>mkdir repo &amp;&amp; cd repo</code>\r\n\r\n<h5>Step 12</h5>\r\nNext, we will <strong>create a new directory called \'sitename.git\' and move into it</strong>. I\'m just going to call mine \'kittens\'.\r\n\r\n<code>mkdir kittens.git &amp;&amp; cd kittens.git</code>\r\n\r\n<h5>Step 3</h5>\r\nNice! Now we need to make this into a bare repository.\r\n\r\n<code>git init --bare</code>\r\n\r\nAnd then move into the \'hooks\' directory:\r\n<code>cd hooks</code>\r\n\r\n\r\nIn this hooks directory, there will be a file called \'post-receive\'. <strong>This is what we are going to use in order to deploy our files on the server.</strong> Essentially, we will tell Git: \"Hey! When you receive a push over here - I want you to take it and deploy the files in my site folder please - k thx!\" (Git replies something like: \"k cool, whatevs\").\r\n\r\nHere\'s what we need to put in that your post-receive file:\r\n\r\n<code>#!/bin/sh\r\ngit --work-tree=/home/your_username/your_site_folder.whatever --git-dir=/home/your_username/repo/kittens.git checkout -f</code>\r\n\r\nYou can use \'nano\' or \'vi\' to launch a terminal a based editor in order to enter this line of code (edit the ‘your_username’ to be your actual username and ‘your_site_folder’ oh good grief you know this right!?) and then save the file.\r\n\r\n<h5>Step 4</h5>\r\nNext - we need to <strong>make that post-receive file executable</strong>. It\'s like giving it superpowers.\r\n\r\n\r\n<code>chmod +x post-receive</code>\r\n\r\n<h5>Step 5</h5>\r\nNow you can bail out of the server! Woot! Until we meet again, Skymaster. Until we meet again. Back in your local project, you\'ll need to <strong>add a remote connection</strong> to your site. It will look something like this:\r\n\r\n<code>git remote add dreamhost ssh://your_username@your_site_name.whatever/home/your_username/repo/kittens.git</code>\r\n\r\nI know.\r\n\r\nThen - you\'ll <strong>push up those files</strong>!\r\n\r\n<code>git push dreamhost master</code>\r\n\r\nThen you dance!!!\r\n\r\nThis is only half of the equation, of course - in order to fully migrate your site, you\'ll also need to move over your database - but the point here is, folks - that you can now deploy your file changes using Git instead of stupid SFTP and you will feel like a total badass.\r\n\r\nSKYMASTERRRRRRRRRR!!!','How to deploy with Dreamhost using Git','You have a local project, you\'ve put it under version control and now you want to use Git\'s awesome powers to push all of your files over to your live site - because SFTP blows. ','inherit','closed','closed','','47838-revision-v1','','','2017-05-30 14:31:27','2017-05-30 14:31:27','',47838,'https://redrambles.blog//47838-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(47861,1,'2017-05-30 14:33:51','2017-05-30 14:33:51','You have a local project, you\'ve put it under version control and now you want to use Git\'s awesome powers to push all of your files over to your live site - because SFTP blows. Right?! Dreamhost say that they support Git, so I figured - righto - let\'s get this show on the road!\r\n\r\nEhhhhhh - This is where things got murky - at least for me. The documentation I unearthed was incomplete at best. Though Git <strong>is</strong> already installed on my Dreamhost server, that was pretty much the end of git support, at least in so far as I found. (sad emoji)\r\n\r\nSo! I decided to do what I always do in these situations: pour myself a glass of wine, put on some good tunes, crack open my terminal and hack at things until I get the result I\'m after. Once I was successful (yay!) - I put together a neat little list of notes that I will share with you here, to hopefully spare you some unnecessary pain.\r\n\r\n<h5>Step 1</h5>\r\n<strong>SSH into your server.</strong>\r\nThis is the first thing. You need to get shell access and be able to log in. The first thing you\'ll see when you log in is this. <img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-47839\" src=\"https://redrambles.blog//wp-content/uploads/2017/05/skymaster.png\" alt=\"skymaster\" width=\"467\" height=\"234\" /> I went around the house saying \'SKYMASTEERRRRRR\' for an hour - bless you if this also brought you joy. Also could have been the wine.\r\n\r\n Once you\'ve gotten over the Skymaster thing, you\'ll find that you are in your home directory. You should see a site folder there called \'name-you-picked.dreamhoster.com\' if you are using the temporary domain that you are given when you sign up. If you linked your own domain to Dreamhost - you will see your domain name there \'your-awesome-domain-name.something\'. \r\n\r\n<strong>We are going to create another directory to keep our site directory company, called \'repo\' </strong> - and then we will move into it.\r\n\r\n\r\n<code>mkdir repo &amp;&amp; cd repo</code>\r\n\r\n<h5>Step 2</h5>\r\nNext, we will <strong>create a new directory called \'sitename.git\' and move into it</strong>. I\'m just going to call mine \'kittens\'.\r\n\r\n<code>mkdir kittens.git &amp;&amp; cd kittens.git</code>\r\n\r\n<h5>Step 3</h5>\r\nNice! Now we need to make this into a bare repository.\r\n\r\n<code>git init --bare</code>\r\n\r\nAnd then move into the \'hooks\' directory:\r\n<code>cd hooks</code>\r\n\r\n\r\nIn this hooks directory, there will be a file called \'post-receive\'. <strong>This is what we are going to use in order to deploy our files on the server.</strong> Essentially, we will tell Git: \"Hey! When you receive a push over here - I want you to take it and deploy the files in my site folder please - k thx!\" (Git replies something like: \"k cool, whatevs\").\r\n\r\nHere\'s what we need to put in that your post-receive file:\r\n\r\n<code>#!/bin/sh\r\ngit --work-tree=/home/your_username/your_site_folder.whatever --git-dir=/home/your_username/repo/kittens.git checkout -f</code>\r\n\r\nYou can use \'nano\' or \'vi\' to launch a terminal a based editor in order to enter this line of code (edit the ‘your_username’ to be your actual username and ‘your_site_folder’ oh good grief you know this right!?) and then save the file.\r\n\r\n<h5>Step 4</h5>\r\nNext - we need to <strong>make that post-receive file executable</strong>. It\'s like giving it superpowers.\r\n\r\n\r\n<code>chmod +x post-receive</code>\r\n\r\n<h5>Step 5</h5>\r\nNow you can bail out of the server! Woot! Until we meet again, Skymaster. Until we meet again. Back in your local project, you\'ll need to <strong>add a remote connection</strong> to your site. It will look something like this:\r\n\r\n<code>git remote add dreamhost ssh://your_username@your_site_name.whatever/home/your_username/repo/kittens.git</code>\r\n\r\nI know.\r\n\r\nThen - you\'ll <strong>push up those files</strong>!\r\n\r\n<code>git push dreamhost master</code>\r\n\r\nThen you dance!!!\r\n\r\nThis is only half of the equation, of course - in order to fully migrate your site, you\'ll also need to move over your database - but the point here is, folks - that you can now deploy your file changes using Git instead of stupid SFTP and you will feel like a total badass.\r\n\r\nSKYMASTERRRRRRRRRR!!!','How to deploy with Dreamhost using Git','You have a local project, you\'ve put it under version control and now you want to use Git\'s awesome powers to push all of your files over to your live site - because SFTP blows. ','inherit','closed','closed','','47838-revision-v1','','','2017-05-30 14:33:51','2017-05-30 14:33:51','',47838,'https://redrambles.blog//47838-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(47862,1,'2017-05-30 14:34:36','2017-05-30 14:34:36','You have a local project, you\'ve put it under version control and now you want to use Git\'s awesome powers to push all of your files over to your live site - because SFTP blows. Right?! Dreamhost say that they support Git, so I figured - righto - let\'s get this show on the road!\r\n\r\nEhhhhhh - This is where things got murky - at least for me. The documentation I unearthed was incomplete at best. Though Git <strong>is</strong> already installed on my Dreamhost server, that was pretty much the end of git support, at least in so far as I found. (sad emoji)\r\n\r\nSo! I decided to do what I always do in these situations: pour myself a glass of wine, put on some good tunes, crack open my terminal and hack at things until I get the result I\'m after. Once I was successful (yay!) - I put together a neat little list of notes that I will share with you here, to hopefully spare you some unnecessary pain.\r\n\r\n<h5>Step 1</h5>\r\n<strong>SSH into your server.</strong>\r\n<p>This is the first thing. You need to get shell access and be able to log in. The first thing you\'ll see when you log in is this. <img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-47839\" src=\"https://redrambles.blog//wp-content/uploads/2017/05/skymaster.png\" alt=\"skymaster\" width=\"467\" height=\"234\" /> I went around the house saying \'SKYMASTEERRRRRR\' for an hour - bless you if this also brought you joy. Also could have been the wine.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Once you\'ve gotten over the Skymaster thing, you\'ll find that you are in your home directory. You should see a site folder there called \'name-you-picked.dreamhoster.com\' if you are using the temporary domain that you are given when you sign up. If you linked your own domain to Dreamhost - you will see your domain name there \'your-awesome-domain-name.something\'.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>We are going to create another directory to keep our site directory company, called \'repo\' </strong> - and then we will move into it.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n<code>mkdir repo &amp;&amp; cd repo</code>\r\n\r\n<h5>Step 2</h5>\r\nNext, we will <strong>create a new directory called \'sitename.git\' and move into it</strong>. I\'m just going to call mine \'kittens\'.\r\n\r\n<code>mkdir kittens.git &amp;&amp; cd kittens.git</code>\r\n\r\n<h5>Step 3</h5>\r\nNice! Now we need to make this into a bare repository.\r\n\r\n<code>git init --bare</code>\r\n\r\nAnd then move into the \'hooks\' directory:\r\n<code>cd hooks</code>\r\n\r\n\r\nIn this hooks directory, there will be a file called \'post-receive\'. <strong>This is what we are going to use in order to deploy our files on the server.</strong> Essentially, we will tell Git: \"Hey! When you receive a push over here - I want you to take it and deploy the files in my site folder please - k thx!\" (Git replies something like: \"k cool, whatevs\").\r\n\r\nHere\'s what we need to put in that your post-receive file:\r\n\r\n<code>#!/bin/sh\r\ngit --work-tree=/home/your_username/your_site_folder.whatever --git-dir=/home/your_username/repo/kittens.git checkout -f</code>\r\n\r\nYou can use \'nano\' or \'vi\' to launch a terminal a based editor in order to enter this line of code (edit the ‘your_username’ to be your actual username and ‘your_site_folder’ oh good grief you know this right!?) and then save the file.\r\n\r\n<h5>Step 4</h5>\r\nNext - we need to <strong>make that post-receive file executable</strong>. It\'s like giving it superpowers.\r\n\r\n\r\n<code>chmod +x post-receive</code>\r\n\r\n<h5>Step 5</h5>\r\nNow you can bail out of the server! Woot! Until we meet again, Skymaster. Until we meet again. Back in your local project, you\'ll need to <strong>add a remote connection</strong> to your site. It will look something like this:\r\n\r\n<code>git remote add dreamhost ssh://your_username@your_site_name.whatever/home/your_username/repo/kittens.git</code>\r\n\r\nI know.\r\n\r\nThen - you\'ll <strong>push up those files</strong>!\r\n\r\n<code>git push dreamhost master</code>\r\n\r\nThen you dance!!!\r\n\r\nThis is only half of the equation, of course - in order to fully migrate your site, you\'ll also need to move over your database - but the point here is, folks - that you can now deploy your file changes using Git instead of stupid SFTP and you will feel like a total badass.\r\n\r\nSKYMASTERRRRRRRRRR!!!','How to deploy with Dreamhost using Git','You have a local project, you\'ve put it under version control and now you want to use Git\'s awesome powers to push all of your files over to your live site - because SFTP blows. ','inherit','closed','closed','','47838-revision-v1','','','2017-05-30 14:34:36','2017-05-30 14:34:36','',47838,'https://redrambles.blog//47838-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(47863,1,'2017-05-30 14:35:03','2017-05-30 14:35:03','You have a local project, you\'ve put it under version control and now you want to use Git\'s awesome powers to push all of your files over to your live site - because SFTP blows. Right?! Dreamhost say that they support Git, so I figured - righto - let\'s get this show on the road!\r\n\r\nEhhhhhh - This is where things got murky - at least for me. The documentation I unearthed was incomplete at best. Though Git <strong>is</strong> already installed on my Dreamhost server, that was pretty much the end of git support, at least in so far as I found. (sad emoji)\r\n\r\nSo! I decided to do what I always do in these situations: pour myself a glass of wine, put on some good tunes, crack open my terminal and hack at 